**September 17, 2024**  
**Initial TA Meeting**

Objectives: Our objective for our initial TA meeting with Surya is to build a strong plan to get started for the semester. We want to create a timeline to figure out when to complete our project proposal and figure out milestones for our Design Review

Our discussion with Surya consisted of building milestones for the upcoming month and understanding how to address critical design components. We discussed breaking down our project into smaller subsystems and have more achievable milestones. Finally, we reviewed the importance of maintaining and following a clear schedule to handle the interactions between hardware and software components.

**October 3, 2024**  
**Updated our Design Document**

Objectives: Our objective for our team meeting today is to discuss the outline for our design document. We want to define key requirements for our project and outline the required designs and verifications of our subsystems.

During today’s meeting, we worked on upgrading the design document by first describing the specific subsystems of the projects, technical requirements and testing methods for the subsystems, high-level requirements, and visual/block diagrams. Defining all these key features in our design document allowed us to gain a stronger grasp and understanding of how to begin executing the hardware components of our project. Our state machines and diagrams enabled us to visualize our project better and get a better overview.

**October 10, 2024**  
**Sensor Integration**

Objective: Figure out what exact sensors we want to use to integrate with the ESP32 microcontroller. By discussing our sensor integration, we will be able to figure out various tests and build an algorithm for our readings

Today, we discussed additional sensors that we can use on top of the soil moisture sensors in order to build a comprehensive understanding of the environmental factors a plant is in. We decided to use temperature/humidity sensors in addition to the soil moisture sensors to get a better grasp of a plant’s setting. We built an algorithm to take the average of these various sensor readings and determine the optimal amount of water to deliver. We identified the pin mappings on the ESP32, timing considerations, and power requirements for our sensors. We also tried building test case scenarios for our sensors.

**October 23, 2024**  
 **PCB Design and Parts Order**

Objective: Today, our meeting objective is to build the PCB schematics on KiCAD, review and order it, and figure out the parts we need to order.

Today, we successfully built the PCB schematics for our irrigation and sensing subsystems on KICAD and determined the various parts we need to have. In our schematic, we determined the specific connections we need to the ESP32 microcontroller, sensors, voltage regulators, etc. We had to determine the exact amount of voltage, resistance, and current that must flow in various parts of our design. Once we completed our PCB design, we submitted the order of exact parts that will be needed for our design.

**October 30, 2024**  
**Initial Software Design**

Objective: Today, we want to start building the software portion of our design. We wanted to build the code for receiving sensor data and an algorithm for using this data to control the motor driver. 

Today, we were able to build the software to get the readings from our various sensors and display them on Serial Output. Although it was difficult to get the Arduino IDE working with the DevKits as we were running into Port issues, we finally got it connected. We also unit tested the irrigation system and were able to get the valve opening and closing with predefined constant inputs. We began testing the BLE communication between the 2 ESP32 dev kits.

**November 5, 2024**  
**BLE Testing**

Objective: Our objective is to complete the BLE tests to transmit data from our sensors to the irrigation system. 

Today, we successfully transmitted the data read from our sensors to the motor driver. We were able to test this by printing on the serial port when data was sent from one dev kit and when the data was received on the other dev kit. Our testing setup involved using 2 ESP32 dev kits powered by USB and at a space of 2 meters. 

[https://docs.arduino.cc/libraries/esp32-ble-arduino/](https://docs.arduino.cc/libraries/esp32-ble-arduino/)  
**November 12, 2024**  
**Second PCB Order**

Objective: The objective of this meeting is to discuss our second PCB order and add the missing programming interface. Then we should submit an order for the new parts.

Today, we updated our initial PCB schematic on KiCAD as we forgot to add a programming interface to our design. WIth the help of a TA and the course WIki page, we added the various parts of the programming interface and resubmitted our design. We updated our schematics, re-routed our new circuit, and built our new parts.

**November 14, 2024**  
**Second BLE Testing**

Objective: Today we want to further test our BLE transmission among dev kits and extend the range and robustness of our system.

Today, we were able to test our BLE further and focus on expanding its range to demonstrate its usage in a real world setting. During our initial BLE testing, we worked with a range of 2 meters but this time, we expanded to 10 meters with obstacles in between to simulate real-world conditions. We found that signal strength decreased but through further tests and error-handling mechanisms, we were able to ensure our BLE works with larger distances.

**November 19, 2024**  
**Combining the Subsystems**

Objective: We know that our subsystems work through unit tests but haven’t combined everything together and determined remaining parts to order. Our objective is to ensure the sensor readings are transmitted to the motor driver and the valve opens and closes.

Today, we retested and ensured that our sensors were providing accurate coding and transmitted the code via BLE. We integrated our BLE code with our sensor code to transmit it. Then, we integrated the BLE receiving code with the irrigation system code and attempted to open and close our valves. We faced a few issues while attempting to finally control the valves and dispense water based on our sensor readings. Some issues were that the motor drivers weren’t outputting enough voltage, the pipes to connect the valves and flow sensors were too large, and we needed a dry plant to get proper readings for our sensor.

**December 1, 2024**  
**Prepping for Final Demo**

Objective: Gather the remaining parts needed to build the system for the Final Demo. Debug the issues we faced from the previous meeting and ensure that the valve opens and closes properly based on the sensor readings. Be fully prepared for the final demo.

Today, we first went to Home Depot to buy new parts to build the system for our final demo. We bought a new rubber pipe to help us connect the network of pump, valve, flow meter and eventually allow water to the plant. After connecting this, we still noticed that the motor driver wasn’t outputting any voltage and our valves weren’t changing. We then realized that our wires were too thin and couldn't carry enough current to the valves. We replaced these motor driver output wires with thicker wires and used a voltmeter to verify that everything was working properly. Finally, the valves were opening and closing as per our sensor readings and we are now ready for the final demo.
